<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-10-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-10-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="600" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d600">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Taylor</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-10-15"><hi rend="italic">October 15,
                                1896</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Notwithstanding promise minister foreign affairs, as stated in your cable
                            10th, exportation of tobacco purchased before decree is still
                            prohibited. It was prohibited only yesterday in clearest possible case
                            of Hernsheim Bros. &amp; Co., New Orleans, represented in Habana by
                            Neuhaus, Newman &amp; Co.</p>
                        <p>Represent fact to minister for foreign affairs, and ask for peremptory
                            telegraphic instruction to Cuban authorities that exportation be
                            allowed.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Olney.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>